Farmers in northern KwaZulu-Natal are very worried about an outbreak of a bacterial disease - Brucellosis - that's transmitted from animals to humans. It's the worst outbreak in three years. #eNCA #DStv403  DURBAN - There is panic among rural farmers in northern KwaZulu-Natal after a reported outbreak of a bacterial disease -- Brucellosis -- that's transmitted from animals to humans. It's the worst outbreak in three years. READ: COVID-19: African Farmers Association donates cattle in KZN The agriculture department in the province is cautioning the public not to drink unpasteurised milk or eat raw meat. More than 400 cows have tested positive this year in northern KwaZulu-Natal, and agriculture officials are concerned the outbreak could trigger reproductive health, nutritional and economic problems. According to the National Institute for Communicable Diseases, humans can be infected with Brucellosis, by drinking unpasteurised milk. Symptoms include fever, headache, night sweats, fatigue and weight loss. READ: Over 15, 000 cattle affected by foot-and-mouth disease The disease is easily treatable with antibiotics if diagnosed early. Meanwhile, a state veterinarian, working closely with the farmers says the disease has been affecting livestock in the area for some time. He has raised concerns that farmers are reluctant to vaccinate their livestock, which might have contributed to the spike. A vaccination drive for calves between the ages of four and eight months is currently underway in all dip tanks in the uMkhanyakude District. * eNCA’s Lethiwe Mdluli reports.